<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920124-0115</DOCNO><DOCID>920124-0115.</DOCID><HL>   American Red Cross Faces   Big Deficit in Relief Fund</HL><DATE>01/24/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The American Red Cross, reeling from severalyears of record-breaking disasters, said its disaster relieffund is experiencing a $28 million shortage so far thisfiscal year.   The organization, although mandated by Congress to be theprimary voluntary group to respond in times of disaster, isfunded by public and corporate donations. &quot;We are indesperate need of financial contributions,&quot; said ElizabethDole, Red Cross president.</LP><TEXT>   The organization's fiscal year ends in June and it isstill facing the flood and tornado seasons, a spokesman said.&quot;We'll continue to operate and provide disaster relief,although it will be jeopardized,&quot; he said.   During the last fiscal year, the Red Cross said itexperienced its worst year in history in terms of the numberof major disasters it faced, providing national assistancefor more than 8,000 victims of disasters. Red Cross disasterrelief in fiscal 1990-91 totaled $184 million. In the prioryear ended in June 1990, though, it paid out even more inrelief, $224 million. That period included Hurricane Hugo inthe southeastern U.S. and the northern California earthquake.   Already in the first six months of 1992, the agency saidit has responded to such major disasters as the Oakland Hillsfire in California, the New England coastal storms and severeflooding in Texas.</TEXT></DOC>